      • setField

        public static int setField​(int i,
                           int y,
                           int f,
                           int A)
        Field assignment function. This function returns the A word after overwriting the field at position i with y. Only the f lower bits of y are considered when setting the field in A. In other words, the bits between f and w in y are disregarded and do not influence the result of this operation.
        Parameters:
        A - The word containing fields.
        i - The position of the first field to return.
        y - The field to be assigned in A.
        f - The length of the fields in A.
        Returns:
        returns the word A after the operation.

      • rankLemma1

        public static int rankLemma1​(long x,
                             long A,
                             int m,
                             int b)
        Implementation of Rank Lemma 1. Lemma 1: Let mb ≤ w. If we are given a b-bit number x and a word A with m b-bit numbers stored in sorted order, then in constant time we can find the rank of x in A, denoted rank(x, A). In order for this method to return sound results the fields in A must be sorted.
        Parameters:
        x - The query of b length.
        A - The word containing the keys to be used in the comparison.
        m - The number of keys in A.
        b - The length of each key in A in bits.
        Returns:
        The rank of x among the keys in A.

      • rankLemma1Verbose

        public static int rankLemma1Verbose​(long x,
                                    long A,
                                    int m,
                                    int b)
        Implementation of Rank Lemma 1, verbose version. Lemma 1: Let mb ≤ w. If we are given a b-bit number x and a word A with m b-bit numbers stored in sorted order, then in constant time we can find the rank of x in A, denoted rank(x, A). In order for this method to return sound results the fields in A must be sorted.
        Parameters:
        x - The query of b length.
        A - The word containing the keys to be used in the comparison.
        m - The number of keys in A.
        b - The length of each key in A in bits.
        Returns:
        The rank of x among the keys in A.
